{"title_page": "United States Marine Corps rank insignia", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[File:IwoJima Homage Insignia Devices.jpg|thumb|Various Marine and Navy rank insignia (as well as [[Badges of the United States Marine Corps|other devices]]) left at the summit of Mount Suribachi on [[Iwo Jima]].]]\n\n==Commissioned officers==\n[[Officer (armed forces)|Commissioned officers]] are distinguished from other officers by their ''[[Commission (document)|commission]]'', which is the formal written authority, issued in the name of the [[President of the United States]], that confers the rank and authority of a Marine Officer. Commissioned officers carry the \"special trust and confidence\" of the President of the United States.<ref name=\"Estes\">{{Cite book\n  | last = Estes\n  | first = Kenneth W.\n  | authorlink =\n  | title = The Marine Officer's Guide, 6th Edition\n  | publisher = Naval Institute Press\n  | year = 2000\n  | location =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | isbn = 1-55750-567-5 }}</ref> Commissioned officer ranks are further subdivided into [[general officer]]s, [[field officer|field-grade officer]]s, and [[company-grade officer]]s. The highest billets in the Marine Corps, the [[Commandant of the Marine Corps]] and the [[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]] are, by statute, [[four-star rank]]s, as the Marine Corps is a separate naval service under the Department of the Navy.<ref name=\"USC10\">{{UnitedStatesCode|10|5043}} & {{UnitedStatesCode|10|5044}}: [[Commandant of the Marine Corps]] & [[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]].</ref>\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"100%\" class=\"wikitable\"\n!Officer\n!colspan=3| '''[[Company-grade officer]]s'''\n!colspan=3| '''[[Field officer|Field-grade officer]]s'''\n!colspan=4| '''[[General officer]]s'''\n|-\n!Title<br />(Abbreviation)\n![[Second Lieutenant#United States|Second lieutenant]]<br />(2ndLt)\n![[First Lieutenant#United States|First lieutenant]]<br />(1stLt)\n![[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]<br />(Capt)\n![[Major (United States)|Major]]<br />(Maj)\n![[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]]<br />(LtCol)\n![[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]<br />(Col)\n![[Brigadier General (United States)|Brigadier general]]<br />(BGen)\n![[Major General (United States)|Major general]]<br />(MajGen)\n![[Lieutenant General (United States)|Lieutenant general]]<br />(LtGen)\n![[General (United States)|General]]<br />(Gen)\n|-\n!'''[[U.S. uniformed services pay grades#Officer pay grades|US DoD Pay Grade]]'''\n!O-1\n!O-2\n!O-3\n!O-4\n!O-5\n!O-6\n!O-7\n!O-8\n!O-9\n!O-10\n|-\n![[Ranks and insignia of NATO#Definitions|NATO Code]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|OF-1\n!OF-2\n!OF-3\n!OF-4\n!OF-5\n!OF-6\n!OF-7\n!OF-8\n!OF-9\n|-\n!Insignia\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US-OF1B.svg|center|15px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US-O2_insignia.svg|center|15px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:U.S. O-3 insignia (USN, USMC, USCG, NOAA, USPHS).svg|center|35px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|center|35px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|center|35px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|center|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|center|30px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:USN-USMC O8 insignia.svg|center|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:USN-USMC O9 insignia.svg|center|90px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:USN-USMC O10 insignia.svg|center|120px]]\n|-\n!Marine Service Uniform Insignia\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O1 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O2 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O3 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O4 shoulderboard-2.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O5 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O6 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O7 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O8 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine O9 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"10%\"| [[File:US Marine 10 shoulderboard vertical.svg|50px]]\n|}\n\n==Warrant officers==\n{{See also|Warrant officer (United States)}}\n[[Warrant Officer (United States)|Warrant Officer]]s provide leadership and training in specialized fields and skills. Unlike other nations' militaries (which rank warrant officers as [[SNCO|Staff NCO]] equivalents), the United States military confers warrants and commissions on its arrant officers and classifies them into a separate category senior to all enlisted grades of rank (including officer candidates), cadets, and midshipmen. As warrant officers are officer-level technical specialists they generally do not exercise command outside of their specialty. Warrant officers come primarily from the [[SNCO#United States|staff non-commissioned officer]] (SNCO) ranks.\n\nA chief warrant officer, CWO2\u2013CWO5, serving in the [[List of United States Marine Corps MOS#03 Infantry|MOS 0306]] \"[[Infantry Weapons Officer]]\" carries a special title, \"marine gunner,\" which does not replace his rank. A marine gunner replaces the chief warrant officer insignia on the left collar with a bursting bomb insignia. Other warrant officers are sometimes incorrectly referred to as \"Gunner.\"\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" Andres Campos=\"0\" width=\"100%\" class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=6| '''Warrant Officers'''\n|-\n![[Infantry Weapons Officer]]<br />\"Marine Gunner\"\n! Warrant Officer<br />(WO)\n!Chief Warrant Officer-2<br />(CWO2)\n!Chief Warrant Officer-3<br />(CWO3)\n!Chief Warrant Officer-4<br />(CWO4)\n!Chief Warrant Officer-5<br />(CWO5)\n|-\n!'''[[U.S. uniformed services pay grades#Warrant Officer pay grades|US DoD Pay Grade]]'''\n!W-1\n!W-2\n!W-3\n!W-4\n!W-5\n|-\n![[Ranks and insignia of NATO#Definitions|NATO Code]]\n!WO-1\n!WO-2\n!WO-3\n!WO-4\n!WO-5\n|-\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:USMC CWO Gunner (Dress).png|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:USMC WO1.svg|center|17px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:USMC CWO2.svg|center|17px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:USMC CWO3.svg|center|17px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:USMC CWO4.svg|center|17px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:USMC CWO5.svg|center|17px]]\n|}\n'''\n\n==Enlisted==\nEnlisted Marines with paygrades of E-4 and E-5 are [[non-commissioned officer]]s (NCOs) while those at E-6 and higher are [[Staff Noncommissioned Officer]]s (SNCOs).<ref name=USMC238>{{cite web|title=Marine Corps Ranks|url=http://www.marines.mil/Marines/Ranks.aspx|publisher=United States Marine Corps website|accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>  The E-8 and E-9 levels each have two ranks per pay grade, each with different responsibilities. Gunnery Sergeants (E-7) indicate on their annual evaluations (called \"fitness reports\") their preferred promotional track: Master Sergeant or First Sergeant. The First Sergeant and Sergeant Major ranks are command-oriented [[Senior Enlisted Advisor]]s, with Marines of these ranks serving as the senior enlisted Marines in a unit, charged to assist the commanding officer in matters of discipline, administration, and the morale and welfare of the unit. Master Sergeants and Master Gunnery Sergeants provide technical leadership as occupational specialists in their specific [[Military occupation specialty code|MOS]]. First Sergeants typically serve as the senior enlisted Marine in a [[Company (military unit)|company]], [[Artillery battery|battery]], or other unit at similar echelon, while Sergeants Major serve the same role in [[battalion]]s, [[Squadron (aviation)|squadron]]s, or larger units.<ref>http://work.chron.com/sergeant-major-jobs-descriptions-21426.html. Retrieved 12 August 2016.</ref>\n\nThe [[Sergeant Major of the Marine Corps]] is a billet and with it carries a special rank insignia, conferred on the senior enlisted Marine of the entire Marine Corps, personally selected by the [[Commandant of the Marine Corps]].<ref name=SMMC>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mclm.com/gallery/sgtmaj.html|title=Sergeants Major of the Marine Corps|publisher=Marine Corps Legacy Museum|accessdate=2006-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030422213618/http://mclm.com/gallery/sgtmaj.html|archive-date=2003-04-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> It and the [[Marine Gunner]] are the only billets which rate modified rank insignia in place of the traditional rank insignia.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"100%\" class=\"wikitable\"\n!Enlisted\n!colspan=3| '''Junior enlisted'''\n!colspan=2| '''Non-commissioned officers (NCOs)'''\n!colspan=7| '''Staff non-commissioned officers (SNCOs)'''\n|-\n!Title<br />(Abbreviation)\n![[Private (rank)|Private]]<br />(Pvt)\n![[Private First Class]]<br />(PFC)\n![[Lance Corporal]]<br />(LCpl)\n![[Corporal]]<br />(Cpl)\n![[Sergeant]]<br />(Sgt)\n![[Staff Sergeant]]<br />(SSgt)\n![[Gunnery Sergeant]]<br />(GySgt)\n![[Master Sergeant]]<br />(MSgt)\n![[First Sergeant]]<br />(1stSgt)\n![[Master Gunnery Sergeant]]<br />(MGySgt)\n![[Sergeant Major]]<br />(SgtMaj)\n![[Sergeant Major of the Marine Corps]]<br />(SMMC)\n|-\n!'''[[U.S. uniformed services pay grades#Officer pay grades|US DoD Pay Grade]]'''\n!E-1\n!E-2\n!E-3\n!E-4\n!E-5\n!E-6\n!E-7\n!colspan=2|E-8\n!colspan=3|E-9\n|-\n![[Ranks and insignia of NATO#Definitions|NATO Code]]\n!OR-1\n!OR-2\n!OR-3\n!OR-4\n!OR-5\n!OR-6\n!OR-7\n!colspan=2|OR-8\n!colspan=3|OR-9\n|-\n!Insignia\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| no insignia\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E2.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E3.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E4.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E5.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E6.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E7.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E8-MSG.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E8-1SG.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E9-MGyS.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E9-SGM.svg|center|50px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"8.3%\"| [[File:USMC-E9-SGMMC.svg|center|50px]]\n|}\n\n\nDifferent styles of rank insignia are worn on different [[Uniforms of the United States Marine Corps|Marine uniforms]]:\n[[File:USMC chevrons.png|thumb|left|500px|L to R: Evening Dress coat, Dress Blue coat, Service Dress coat, Service Dress \"B\" and \"C\" shirt, and combat utility pin-on insignia for a Staff Sergeant]]\n{{Clear}}\nGold stripes on a red flash are worn on the Dress Blue uniform coat. Green stripes on a red flash are worn on the Service uniform coat. Rank insignia are worn on the upper sleeve of both coats. Khaki uniform shirts use green stripes on a khaki flash, and are worn on the upper sleeves of both long and short-sleeved shirts. Utility uniform rank insignia are black metal pins and are worn on the collars, or black embroidered insignia sewn into patches of material when wearing armor. Musicians in the [[United States Marine Band]] wear insignia with [[lyre]] in the center as opposed to the crossed rifles, to denote their lack of a combat mission; full-service Marines who are attached to the 10 field bands of the [[United States Marine Corps#Organization|Operating Forces and Supporting Establishment]] continue to wear their normal rank insignia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chapter 6: Musical Units|url=http://www.marcorsyscom.usmc.mil/sites/mcub/library/MCUR/URCH6.htm#UR6100|work=Marine Corps Uniform Regulations|publisher=Marine Corps Systems Command|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> The crossed M1 rifles insignia were added to E-3 through E-8 chevrons in 1959.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|War}}\n* [[British and United States military ranks compared]]\n* [[Comparative military ranks]]\n* [[List of United States Marine Corps acronyms and expressions]] for more nicknames and forms of address\n* [[Ranks and insignia of NATO]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Marine Corps}}\n* {{Cite book|url=http://www.marines.mil/news/publications/Pages/MCO%20P1070.12K%20W%20CH%201.aspx|title=MCO P1070-12K: Individual Records Administration Manual|publisher=United States Marine Corps|accessdate=2008-10-03}}\n* {{cite book|url=http://www.tecom.usmc.mil/HD/PDF_Files/Pubs/ranks%20and%20grades%201775-1969.pdf|title=United States Marine Corps Ranks and Grades, 1775\u20131962|first=Bernard C.|last=Nalty|author2=Truman R. Strobridge |author3=Edwin T. Turnbladh |year=1962|publisher=[[United States Marine Corps History Division|Historical Division]], United States Marine Corps|format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.leatherneck.com/forums/showthread.php?t=61015 USMC Rank Chevrons through the ages...since 1917]\n* [http://www.military-ranks.org/marine-corps Marine Corps ranks]\n\n{{US Marine Corps navbox}}\n{{US armed forces insignia navigation}}\n{{US officer ranks|collapse=collapsed}}\n{{US enlisted ranks}}\n{{United States Armed Forces}}\n{{Military ranks by country}}\n\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps ranks| ]]\n[[Category:Military insignia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n[[File:IwoJima Homage Insignia Devices.jpg|thumb|Various Marine and Navy rank insignia (as well as [[Badges of the United States Marine Corps|other devices]]) left at the summit of Mount Suribachi on [[Iwo Jima]].]]\n\n==Commissioned officers==\n[[Officer (armed forces)|Commissioned officers]] are distinguished from other officers by their ''[[Commission (document)|commission]]'', which is the formal written authority, issued in the name of the [[President of the United States]], that confers the rank and authority of a Marine Officer. Commissioned officers carry the \"special trust and confidence\" of the President of the United States.<ref name=\"Estes\">{{Cite book\n  | last = Estes\n  | first = Kenneth W.\n  | authorlink =\n  | title = The Marine Officer's Guide, 6th Edition\n  | publisher = Naval Institute Press\n  | year = 2000\n  | location =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | isbn = 1-55750-567-5 }}</ref> Commissioned officer ranks are further subdivided into [[general officer]]s, [[field officer|field-grade officer]]s, and [[company-grade officer]]s. The highest billets in the Marine Corps, the [[Commandant of the Marine Corps]] and the [[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]] are, by statute, [[four-star rank]]s, as the Marine Corps is a separate naval service under the Department of the Navy.<ref name=\"USC10\">{{UnitedStatesCode|10|5043}} & {{UnitedStatesCode|10|5044}}: [[Commandant of the Marine Corps]] & [[Assistant Commandant of the Marine Corps]].</ref>\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"100%\" class=\"wikitable\"\n!Officer\n!colspan=3| '''[[Company-grade officer]]s'''\n!colspan=3| '''[[Field officer|Field-grade officer]]s'''\n!colspan=4| '''[[General officer]]s'''\n|-\n!Title<br />(Abbreviation)\n![[Second Lieutenant#United States|Second lieutenant]]<br />(2ndLt)\n![[First Lieutenant#United States|First lieutenant]]<br />(1stLt)\n![[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]<br />(Capt)\n![[Major (United States)|Major]]<br />(Maj)\n![[Lieutenant Colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]]<br />(LtCol)\n![[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]<br />(Col)\n![[Brigadier General (United States)|Brigadier general]]<br />(BGen)\n![[Major General (United States)|Major general]]<br 